Graphical abstract An efficient synthesis of magnetically separable iron oxide nanoparticles and their application as a recyclable catalyst for acylation of phenols, alcohols, and amines by sonication under solvent free condition at room temperature has been reported. This paper reports a facile synthesis of magnetically separable iron oxide (γ-Fe2O3) nanoparticles using thermolysis method. The structural and morphological study of the synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles was carried out using X-ray diffraction (XRD), field emission gun–scanning electron microscopy (FEG–SEM), energy dispersive X-ray spectrum (EDS), transmission electron microscopy (TEM), Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR), thermogravimetric analysis (TGA), and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) techniques. The electron microscopy reveals that the γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles have spherical morphology with a particle size in the range of 40–100nm. The XPS study confirmed the Fe is in +3 oxidation state. The synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles have been used as an efficient heterogeneous catalyst for the organic transformation between phenols, alcohols, and amines with acetic anhydride under sonication using mild reaction conditions. Various electrons withdrawing and electrons donating substrates show an excellent yield of desired products with the advantage of magnetic separation and reusability of γ-Fe2O3 nanocatalyst. Keywords γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles Thermolysis Characterization X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy Coupling reaction 1 Introduction The synthesis of nanoparticles has been receiving increasing interest in the current research due to their extraordinary physicochemical properties as compared to their bulk counterparts. The fabrication of nanoparticles using green methodologies which can control nucleation and propagation, to get size and shape selective nanoparticles is one of the challenging tasks [1]. Iron oxide is an important inorganic material having magnetic properties as well as good stability in aqueous dispersion [2]. Particularly, Fe2O3 nanoparticles find wide applications in gas sensing [3], Li-ion batteries [4,5], magnetizations and water treatment [6,7], hydrogen production [8], cancer treatment [9], surface enhanced Raman scattering and electrocatalysis [10], degradation of pharmaceutical compounds [11], supercapacitor [12], and as a heterogeneous catalyst [13–15]. In literature, the functionalized iron oxide nanoparticles are synthesized using various methods and are used in biodiesel production [16], photodegradation of hexachlorocyclohexane [17], removal of fluoride in water [18], and catalysis [19,20]. Several methods are reported to synthesize iron oxide nanoparticles, including hydrothermal [21], solvothermal [22], co-precipitation [23], forced hydrolysis [24], electron beam irradiation [25], microemulsion [26], sonochemical [27], and biosynthetic methods [28,29]. Recently, Taniguchi et al. reported hydrothermal synthesis of iron oxide nanoparticles using stainless steel autoclave [21], but the methodology has limitations, such as use of high temperature (up to 230°C), longer reaction time, and requirement of pressure. Almeida et al . demonstrated the synthesis of iron oxide nanoparticles by hydrothermal method in a Teflon-lined steel autoclave [30]. Nemati et al . synthesized iron oxide nanoparticles by hydrothermal route [31]. These protocols achieve particles in nano region, but they have one or more drawbacks as mentioned above. Therefore, there is a need to develop an alternative method which can be simple, economical, and greener for the synthesis of iron oxide nanoparticles. Nowadays, current research is not only focused on development of simple and greener routes for the synthesis of morphology controlled nanoparticles, but is also focused on their applications in various fields. Magnetic separable nanoparticles show good catalytic activity in catalysis because of high surface area, high mechanical stability, increasing contacts between catalyst and reactants, and good dispersion in reaction mixture. The magnetic separable nanoparticles have advantages, such as insoluble in reaction mixture, paramagnetic nature, and easy separation of nanocatalyst by using magnet which avoids the catalyst filtration; it prevents the aggregation of nanocatalyst which increases the durability of the catalysts, recycling, and reusability of catalyst [32]. The researchers paid their efforts to the synthesis of magnetic separable nanoparticles and their applications in catalysis [33–35]. In our recent work, we have developed several facile and greener synthetic routes for nanoparticles and developed their applications in catalysis [36–40]. In the present work, we have developed an efficient method for the synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles by thermolysis method. Herein, iron acetylacetonate is used as a starting material, oleic acid as surfactant which prevents the agglomeration of particles, n-butylamine and 1,6-hexandiol acts as a binding or capping agent as well as responsible to control the morphology of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. Furthermore, we have shown the application of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles in organic reaction for the coupling of phenols, alcohols, and amines with acetic anhydride using sonication energy. The synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles exhibit good catalytic activity for the reaction with an advantage of catalyst recyclability. The catalyst could be reused up to fourth run without loss of catalytic activity. Notably the reaction works under low catalyst loading, solvent free condition, at room temperature (28°C) and first time demonstrates the use of simple sonication energy for this organic coupling reaction with catalyst recyclability. This is a facile technique for synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles and it can also be further extended for synthesis of other metal oxides. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials A.R. grade iron acetylacetonate [Fe(acac)3] was procured from Spectrochem Pvt., Ltd., India. n-butylamine, oleic acid and 1,6-hexandiol were procured from S.D. Fine Chemicals Pvt., Ltd., India. All chemicals were of high purity and were used without further purification. 2.2 Synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles In a typical method for the synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles, a mixture of 200mg (0.57mmol) of iron acetylacetonate with 6mL of n-butylamine and 1mL of oleic acid were taken in a 100mL round bottom flask. 1,6-hexanediol (492mg, 4.16mmol) was added under stirring to the above mixture at room temperature. The reaction flask was sealed tightly with lid using the Teflon tape around it. The reaction mixture was stirred vigorously with magnetic stirrer at 100°C for 2h. A red color precipitate was observed indicating the formation of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. After completion of reaction, the reaction mass was diluted with distilled water and centrifuged at 8000rpm for 10min. The product was washed with distilled water and absolute ethanol several times and dried at 70°C in oven. The obtained nanoparticles were characterized by different analytical techniques. 2.3 Method of characterization of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles As prepared γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles were characterized by X-ray diffractometer (Shimadzu XRD-6100 using CuKα radiations=1.5405Å) with scanning rate 2° per min and 2 theta (θ) angle ranging from 20° to 75° at current 30.0mA and voltage 40.0kW. The morphology of the sample was examined by field emission gun–scanning electron microscopy (FEG–SEM) analysis using Tescan MIRA 3 model and transmission electron microscopy (TEM) using JEOL JEM-2100 in ISSP, operating voltage at 200kV. The energy dispersive X-ray spectrum (EDS) was recorded by using INCA x-act Oxford instrument (Model 51-ADD0007). X-ray photoelectron spectra (XPS) were monitored by using PHI 5000 Versa Probe with a monochromatic focused (100μm×100μm) Al Kα X-ray radiation (15kV, 30mA) and duel beam neutralization using a combination of argon ion gun and electron irradiation. Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR) was recorded on JASCO-FTIR-400 spectrometer. Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) was carried out using PerkinElmer STA 6000. Brunauer–Emmett–Teller (BET) surface area and pore size was analyzed on ASAP 2010 (Micromeritics, USA) instrument. 2.4 General procedure for acylation reaction A 25mL sealed tube containing a magnetic stir bar was charged with phenol/alcohol/amine (1mmol) and acetic anhydride (1.5mmol), nano γ-Fe2O3 (5mol%, 8mg) as catalyst. The reaction mixture was kept for sonication in sonication bath at room temperature (28°C) for 1h. The ultrasonic bath (Labman Scientific Instruments, Model – LMUC 4) had a frequency of 33kHz and electric power rating of 100W. The reaction progress was monitored on thin-layer chromatography (TLC) and gas chromatography (PerkinElmer, GC Clarus 400) analysis. After completion of the reaction, the reaction mixture was diluted with ethyl acetate and catalyst was separated from reaction mixture by using a strong magnet. The separated catalyst was washed with distilled water and absolute ethanol several times then dried in oven and reused for further reaction. The reaction mixture was washed with saturated NaHCO3 solution (1×15mL) and the product was extracted with ethyl acetate (3×10mL) and dried over Na2SO4 and evaporated under vacuum. All the obtained products are well known in the literature and were confirmed by gas chromatography–mass spectrometry (Shimadzu GCMS-QP 2010) analysis by comparison with literature data. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Characterization of synthesized Fe2O3 nanoparticles The synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles were characterized by FEG–SEM (Fig. 1 ), which shows that particles are in nano region and spherical in shape along with some aggregation of nanoparticles. Fig. 1 shows FEG–SEM images of the same sample with different magnification. Fig. 1a and b are low magnification FEG–SEM images of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles whereas the Fig. 1c and d are high magnification FEG–SEM images of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles, which indicates that the particle size of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles is in the range of 40–100nm which leads to the availability of high surface area for catalytic activity (see ESI Fig. S2). The particle morphology was examined using TEM analysis. TEM analysis was carried out by dispersing γ-Fe2O3 powder sample in ethanol and then it was exposed to ultrasonication bath for 10min. A drop from this slurry was deposited on a copper grid. The TEM images Fig. 2 a show the low magnification image of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles whereas, Fig. 2b, c, and d are the high magnification images which show spherical morphology with size range of 40–100nm. (see ESI Fig. S3). The morphology and particle size of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles from TEM analysis is in good agreement with results obtained by FEG–SEM analysis. To check the effect of 1,6-hexanediol as a capping agent, we carried out the experiment without 1,6-hexanediol. In surface morphological study, Fig. 3 a and b are the high and low magnification FEG–SEM images respectively, which reveals that there was no specific morphology was observed for this reaction as compared to the reaction carried out in presence 1,6-hexanediol (Fig. 1). This indicates that 1,6-hexanediol is essential to control the crystal morphology of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. The phase identification of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles was carried out using XRD pattern (Fig. 4 ). XRD indicates the (311), (400), (422), (511), (300), and (533) planes, confirm the formation of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. The obtained results from XRD are in good agreement with JCPDS card no. 39-1346. EDS analysis clearly indicates presence of Fe and oxygen elements in the material and confirms the purity of the prepared nanoparticles (Fig. 5 a). In Fig. 5b, a strong absorption band seen at 551cm−1 in FT-IR spectrum of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles indicates the presence of FeO bond. The band at 2846 and 2920cm−1 can be attributed to CH stretching vibrations of alkyl chain, whereas, the band at 1403 and 1532cm−1 can be attributed to the angular deformation of water δHOH, it may also due to absorption peaks of n-butylamine, acetylacetonate, oleic acid, and 1,6-hexanediol. The energy dispersive X-ray elemental mapping for γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles shows that Fe (Fig. 6 b, green) and oxygen (Fig. 6c, red) species coexist in the material. The detailed analysis of the Fe (green) and oxygen (red) mapping reveals that the concentration of oxygen is more than that of Fe. Fig. 7 a shows XPS survey spectrum of the synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles, which show photoelectron peaks of iron (Fe 2p), oxygen (O 1s), and carbon (C 1s) present on the surface. The carbon peak comes from the carbon tape used as support in XPS analysis. The corresponding high resolution XPS spectra at 530.4eV indicates the O 1s region (Fig. 7b) and the high resolution XPS spectra of Fe 2p region shown in Fig. 7c is attributed to presence of Fe2O3. The peak observed at 710.9eV is analogous to Fe 2p3/2 and the peak at 725eV is analogous to Fe 2p1/2. Additional peaks at 719eV and 731.4eV are the two shake-up satellite peaks. The appearance of Fe3+ cations (710.9eV) rather than Fe2+ cations (709eV) indicates the presence of the Fe2O3 phase [41]. The Brunauer–Emmett–Teller (BET) specific surface area of the γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles is an important parameter for the high catalytic activity. Fig. 8 a shows nitrogen adsorption and desorption curve of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. Analysis of the isotherms exhibits 23.8m2/g of the BET surface area. The pore volume and average pore diameter were found to be 0.20cm3/g and 34.7nm, respectively, for the γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. TGA curve (Fig. 8b) indicates weight loss in the range of 80–120°C which is due to the evaporation of moisture absorbed by γ-Fe2O3 material. Another weight loss between 250–360 oC is due to decomposition of organic moieties, such as 1,6-hexanediol (b.p. 208°C) and oleic acid (b.p. 360°C) which were used in the synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. Vibrating sample magnetometer (VSM) analysis gives idea about the magnetic properties of the materials. The MH hysteresis loop for γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles was measured at room temperature (Fig. 9 ). The detail analysis signifies that the magnetization becomes 0.17emu/g. As the particle size decreases, the magnetization also decreases. 3.2 Catalytic application of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles Recently, catalysis research has been focused towards greener and environmentally benign protocols which avoid the use of volatile organic solvents, toxic reagents, harsh reaction conditions, and time-consuming processes [42]. Nanocatalysis has several advantages in research over conventional catalyst systems or bulk materials, such as large surface-to-volume ratio; easy separation; low catalyst loading, and recyclability of catalyst [43]. The use of magnetically separable nanoparticles in catalysis has promising and versatile role in current research due to their insoluble and paramagnetic nature as it enables easy separation of the catalysts from the reaction mixture using external magnet [35,44]. The catalytic activity of synthesized magnetically recoverable γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles was checked for the acylation reaction using phenols, alcohols, and amines with acetic anhydride under solvent free condition using sonication energy at room temperature (28°C) (Scheme 1 ). The sonication energy has several advantages, such as high efficiency, low waste, less energy requirement, it produces cavitation bubbles which increases the interaction between reactant and catalyst, accelerates the reaction speed, provides better mass, and heat transfer efficiency compared to conventional heating, economic, and easy operation [45,46]. Recently, the Azizi and Heydari reported acylation of phenols and alcohols using vitamin B1 supported on silica-encapsulated γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles (nano γ-Fe2O3@SiO2@vitamin B1) [47]. The methodology shows random formation of nanoparticles and does not get the specific shape and size of nanomaterials. It as well suffers from limited substrate scope. Rajabi and Luque have reported Fe/SBA-15 catalyzed acylation of phenols and alcohols [48]. The protocol uses some temperature and high catalyst loading for the reaction. These protocols use support to increase the catalytic activity, but our protocol provides good catalytic activity without using any support. It further uses sonication energy at room temperature. Hoseini et al. have demonstrated the use of Fe3O4 nanoparticles for the Friedel–Crafts acylation reaction of anisole to ortho- and para- directing acylated products [49]. Our protocol uses a variety of different starting reagents and yields O and N acylated products using γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles under sonication at room temperature (28°C). Literature survey reveals that acylation reactions of phenols, alcohols, and amines have been carried out using various catalysts, such as modified Y zeolites [50], amorphous carbon–silica composites bearing sulfonic acid [51], poly(N-vinylimidazole) [52], sulfonic acid [53], titanocene bis(perfluorooctanesulfonate) [54], RuCl3 in [bmim][PF6] ionic liquid [55] 4-(N,N-dimethylamino) pyridine hydrochloride [56], NaCo(CO)4 [57], Ac2O–Py/Al2O3 [58], FeCl2 [59], cobalt(II) salen complex [60], ZnAl2O4@SiO2 nanocomposite [61], BiFeO3 [62], anhydrous NiCl2 [63], thallium(III) chloride [64], ErCl3 [65], Gd(OTf)2 [66], Cu(OTf)2 [67], and nano CdO [68]. Most of these protocols have several disadvantages like use of additives and surfactants, requirement of co-catalysts, longer reaction times, high catalyst loading, and use of homogenous catalysts. To overcome these drawbacks, we explored the catalytic activity of magnetically recoverable γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles for acylation of phenols, alcohols, and amines and found that it gives excellent yield of the corresponding products. Notably, the reaction does not require any additives; reaction works with low catalyst loading, under solvent free conditions with good to excellent yields of the desired products with catalyst recyclability making the protocol attractive. This is one of the simple and ecological protocol for acylation of phenols, alcohols, and amines. Initially, the reaction of phenol with acetic anhydride was chosen as a model reaction and effects of various parameters, such as catalyst loading, catalyst screening and time were studied using sonication bath (Labman Scientific Instruments, Model – LMUC 4 had frequency 33kHz and electric power 100W) under solvent free condition. At the beginning, the reaction was carried out in absence of the catalyst, but reaction did not proceed (Table 1 , entry 1). Then we screened the catalyst loading using model reaction (Table 1, entries 2–5). It was observed that 5mol% of catalyst gives an excellent yield (92%) of the desired product (Table 1, entry 4). We have checked the temperature after completion of reaction; it was observed that temperature rises from 28°C to 36°C at the end of reaction. Along with nano γ-Fe2O3, we also screened various catalysts such as Fe(OAc)2, FeCl3, FeCl2, Fe(NO3)3, Bulk Fe2O3, nano Cu/Cu2O [69], and nano ZnO [70] to increase the reaction outcome (Table 1, entries 4 and 6–12). Among these, the synthesized nano γ-Fe2O3 shows good catalytic activity for the model reaction (Table 1, entry 4). Furthermore, we also investigated the effect of reaction time (Table 1, entries 4, 13, and 14) and it was found that the highest yield of the desired product was obtained within 1hr (Table 1, entry 4). The respective turnover number (TON) for all optimized reaction conditions was included in Table 1. We have investigated the yield of acylation product (42%) after prolong sonication for 2h. In this case, reversible reaction was takes place and observed the formation of starting materials. We have carried out reaction in absence of sonication i.e., room temperature (28°C) with nano γ-Fe2O3, but reaction does not work. We also checked reaction in absence of nano γ-Fe2O3 under long sonication (3h) and studied the effect of sonication on reaction. It was observed that formation of 10% yield of acylation product. Thus, the optimized reaction conditions for acylation reaction were; phenol (1mmol), acetic anhydride (1.5mmol), nano γ-Fe2O3 (5mol%), and sonication for 1h at room temperature. In order to broaden the substrate scope of the developed protocol various derivatives of phenols and alcohols were examined for the acylation reaction (Table 2 ). The reaction with phenols containing electron withdrawing (Table 2, entries 1–6) as well as electron donating substituents (Table 2, entries 7–11) were compatible under the optimized reaction conditions and provided good to excellent yields of the corresponding products. It was observed that the electron withdrawing substituents of phenol gave a good yield as compared to electron donating substituents of phenol. We also studied various substrates of alcohol at optimized reaction conditions and it was observed that alcohols furnish moderate yields of respective products (Table 2, entries 12–16). By considering the above optimized reaction conditions of acylation reaction of phenol we extended the scope of developed protocol for acylation of various derivatives of amines (Table 3 ). The reactions with various derivatives of aromatic amines with electron donating and electron withdrawing groups provided the acylation products in good yields (Table 3, entries 1–4). It was observed that electron donating substituents of amines furnish excellent yield of desired products as compared to electron withdrawing substituents. In addition, we examined aliphatic amines (Table 3, entries 5–8), cyclic amines (Table 3, entries 9 and 10), and heterocyclic amines (Table 3, entries 11 and 12) for the acylation reaction and all amines provide moderate to excellent yield of desired products. In mechanism, the acylation reaction is initiated by coordination of the carbonyl group of acetic anhydride with Fe ion of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles and activation of carbonyl group takes place. The carbonyl group reacts with substrate which acts as a nucleophile and results in to the acetate product (Scheme 2 ). The recyclability of catalyst is a great advantage in reducing the overall cost in process chemistry and decreasing environmental pollution. It eliminates involvement in the synthesis and resale process. We have investigated magnetic separation and reusability of the γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles for the acylation reaction using phenol and acetic anhydride as substrates under solvent free conditions. The γ-Fe2O3 nanocatalyst was reused successfully up to fourth run with excellent catalytic activity (Fig. 10 ). Inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectroscopy (ICP-AES) analysis determines the elemental concentration in the sample. We have checked the leaching of Fe metal from γ-Fe2O3 nanocatalyst by ICP–AES analysis after fourth run and the 1.95wt% concentration of Fe was detected. As shown in the Fig. 11 , after completion of reaction, the reaction mixture was diluted with ethyl acetate and the catalyst was recovered from the reaction mixture by applying strong magnet. The catalyst was washed with distilled water and absolute alcohol several times to remove the organic impurities. The obtained γ-Fe2O3 nanocatalyst was dried in the oven and used as a catalyst for recyclability study (see ESI Fig. S1). The morphological study of fresh nanocatalyst and after the fourth run was shown in Fig. 12 . The Fig. 12a displays FEG–SEM analysis of fresh γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles whereas, Fig. 12b displays FEG–SEM analysis of magnetically recycled γ-Fe2O3 nanocatalyst after the fourth run. The detail analysis of recycled catalyst reveals that nanoparticles are spherical in shape along with somewhat more aggregation of particles (Fig. 12b) than that of fresh nanoparticles (Fig. 12a). 4 Conclusion In summary, a simple and facile protocol for the synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles has been developed using thermolysis method. The n-butylamine and 1,6-hexandiol act as structure inducing agents in the reaction and give spherical morphology to the nanoparticles. It was observed that the synthesis without using 1,6-hexandiol gives random size and shape of the nanoparticles. The presence of 1,6-hexandiol significantly impacts the overall nucleation growth process for the synthesis of γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles. Furthermore, we have shown the catalytic applicability of synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles for coupling reaction of phenols, alcohols, and amines with acetic anhydride using sonication energy (sonication bath) at room temperature. Under the optimized reaction conditions various derivatives of phenols, alcohols, and amines provided good to excellent yield of the respective products with an advantage of catalyst recyclability up to fourth run. coredata.dc:description: This paper reports a facile synthesis of magnetically separable iron oxide (γ-Fe2O3) nanoparticles using thermolysis method. The structural and morphological study of the synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles was carried out using X-ray diffraction (XRD), field emission gun–scanning electron microscopy (FEG–SEM), energy dispersive X-ray spectrum (EDS), transmission electron microscopy (TEM), Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR), thermogravimetric analysis (TGA), and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) techniques. The electron microscopy reveals that the γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles have spherical morphology with a particle size in the range of 40–100nm. The XPS study confirmed the Fe is in +3 oxidation state. The synthesized γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles have been used as an efficient heterogeneous catalyst for the organic transformation between phenols, alcohols, and amines with acetic anhydride under sonication using mild reaction conditions. Various electrons withdrawing and electrons donating substrates show an excellent yield of desired products with the advantage of magnetic separation and reusability of γ-Fe2O3 nanocatalyst.
coredata.dc:title: Magnetically separable γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles: An efficient catalyst for acylation of alcohols, phenols, and amines using sonication energy under solvent free condition
